    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think so. It's just a constant expression and can be computed by <code>#eval</code>. Unlike <code>n+0=n</code>, <code>M 0: Nat</code> is a closed term, which should always be able to be beta-reduced to the constructors. It seems that in the tactic mode we don't actually do <em>computations</em> (beta-reductions).</p>\n<p>Does this mean that <code>simp</code> does not do the beta reduction? Maybe <code>simp</code> only simplifies things by equalities (including those caused by definition)? So if the lemma is missing, I cannot do the computation with <code>simp</code>?</p>",
        "id": 522199698,
        "sender_full_name": "xiao",
        "timestamp": 1748978549
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>simp</code> does do beta-reduction (<code>(fun x =&gt; _) y</code>), zeta-reduction (<code>let x := y; z</code>) and others; but it only unfolds when asked to (or when a definition is tagged <code>@[simp]</code>). In this case it is actually impossible to solve the goal by merely reduction or unfolding since it uses the <code>@[irreducible]</code> function <code>Std.DHashMap.Internal.mkIdx</code>. This is one example of how you can't always reduce to constructors, another is axioms which also block reduction. So really, <code>simp</code> only does something when it's told to through <code>@[simp]</code> lemmas or user-specified lemmas and definition names. The reason <code>3 + 3</code> simplifies to <code>6</code> is because there is a so-called simproc which takes care of it. Similarly, other functions are only evaluated by <code>simp</code> because of lemmas about them (e.g. <code>List.getElem_cons_succ</code>).<br>\nStill, there are tactics that work with \"computations\", e.g. <code>rfl</code>, which works for definitions without reduction blockers. However, \"computation\" is a bit of misleading word for reductions here since the kind of computation <code>#eval</code> does it completely different in nature to the one of <code>rfl</code>; <code>rfl</code> just reduces and is thus not very fast; <code>#eval</code> actually uses the compiler and thus doesn't do any reductions. If you wanted to (although I'd discourage it), you could use <code>native_decide</code> to prove things through <code>#eval</code> (which again, doesn't reduce though!). (Note: the reason <code>native_decide</code> is discouraged is because you additionally rely on the entire compiler and it's not too hard to prove <code>False</code> with it)</p>",
        "id": 522203939,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Arnez",
        "timestamp": 1748980218
    },
